Since this IS a discussion group, allow me to tell you about something that affected me shortly after I returned from Vietnam.<br><br>
I don't think it was a coincidence that the book _Bury My Heart At Wounded Knee_ came out during the war years. Maybe it was, who knows? I have a confession to make, when I watched western movies as a kid, I always rooted for the cowboys. My brother, who is now deceased, always pulled for the Indians. Could never understand why, at least when I was a kid.<br><br>
I can't recall if this was in the book, but I remember, at that time, it being said that the American Indian NEVER broke a treaty it had signed with the US government.<br><br>
Cook, I was in Vietnam a couple of years after you left. There were that many more bomb craters.<br><br>
I can remember going into villages and us having an old papa san or somebody digging away at the mounds of dirt which typically surrounded every house. Sometimes we would find large amounts of rice. This rice was taken and destroyed. It evidentally was too much for them to have. I remember, one time, a mama san pointing to her children, motioning that the rice was for them. This didn't matter to us. Somebody said that she could file a claim with somebody and get rice to replace what we were confiscating from her. Does that make sense? Maybe it was a rice cache for the VC, as it was assumed, maybe it was for her family? We didn't know for sure. We took her rice, anyway.<br><br>
This is the kind of thing that troubled me then, and still does.<br>
 <br>
This was a policy of our government.<br><br>
No, I am not equating Americans in VN with Stalin or Hitler. What I am saying is that we, as a country, must bear a burden for the many things that happened there, and previously in our own country during its foundling years.<br><br>
I have read where 20% of the civilian population was displaced - much of it intentionally, in order to deny the Viet Cong the services or potential sympathies of these people. The result was immense poverty experienced by those living in squalor in overcrowded cities.<br><br>
We talk of the Vietnamese boat people. I live a short drive from the beginning of &quot;The Trail Of Tears&quot;. How many of us shed tears for the Loyalists of our American revolution?<br><br>
We should be more practiced in the art of introspection. Taking a long look at ourselves in the mirror and admitting there are some things that we don't like. We are able to improve, by first admitting, then making, a vow to do better. That we CAN DO better! People should do this, as well as countries. I believe that many in the Peace Movement believed this at that time. We, who served in Vietnam, were representatives of our countrymen. Why didn't they have a right to object to the way the war was waged?<br><br>
This country, that we live in, is the greatest country in the history of man. We have many troubles now, as we have always had, but we can always improve. We should always strive in that direction.<br><br>
There is no excusing the bad treatment that returning vets received. But there is still much work for us to do.<br><br>
Speaking for myself, I refuse to let that long ago homecoming experience translate into bitterness today. Not after what I know, and what I see when I make that occasional look into the mirror.<br><br>

